sentences: Myke Rocco Scavone (born 1949) is an American harmonica player and vocalist best known for his work with the bands the Doughboys and Ram Jam.
He attended North Plainfield High School, graduating as part of the class of 1966, where he would meet the other future members of his first successful band, the Doughboys.
Scavone joined his first band, the Apollos, in December 1964.
He then joined the Ascots in 1965 with another member of the Apollos, guitarist Mike Farina.
They changed their name to The Doughboys in 1966 and secured a contract with Bell Records after winning a battle of the bands contest.
Scavone was dismissed from the Doughboys in early 1968 when they decided to concentrate on instrumental music before disbanding at the end of that year.

Following the disbandment of the Doughboys, Scavone began a career as a session drummer throughout the late 1960s and early 1970s.
Following the disbandment of the Doughboys, Scavone began a career as a session drummer throughout the late 1960s and early 1970s.
He was performing on demos for producers Jerry Kasenetz and Jeffry Katz when he joined the newly formed Ram Jam, led by guitarist Bill Bartlett, in 1977.
Scavone performed on both of the band's albums, Ram Jam and Portrait of the Artist as a Young Ram before the band disbanded in 1978.
Following a period of inactivity in music, Scavone joined a reformed version of the Doughboys in 2000 and still performs with them.
It ended up being a full-time reunion and resulted in the recording of five new albums, Is It Now?
(2007), Act Your Rage (2010), Shakin' Our Souls (2012) and Hot Beat Stew (2015), "Front Street Rebels" (2017), and Running For Covers (2019).
